Comment (policies/secretsmanager_access_administration_events.rego:82):
**`event_secret_id` raises a runtime `eval_conflict_error` on realistic CloudTrail events (medium).** Rego function rules with `:=` heads must produce a single output per input — multiple bodies that succeed with *different* values are a runtime conflict, not a relation. The six `event_secret_id` bodies (lines 43-76) cover the same input shape but read different fields; on a real CloudTrail event that populates more than one (e.g. `requestParameters.secretId == "MySecret"` *and* `resources[].ARN == "arn:aws:secretsmanager:...:secret:MySecret-AbCdEf"`, which is the **default CloudTrail shape** for Secrets Manager API calls), two bodies fire with different values and OPA errors out:

```
eval_conflict_error: functions must not produce multiple outputs for same inputs
  policies/secretsmanager_access_administration_events.rego:72
```

I reproduced this locally by patching one test fixture to use the realistic shape (`requestParameters.secretId` + `resources[].ARN`). The existing tests don't catch it because each test event populates exactly one shape. The same shape exists in [secretsmanager_confidential_disposal_record.rego:73-106](policies/secretsmanager_confidential_disposal_record.rego#L73) — both files break together on the same evidence.

Suggested fix: turn `event_secret_id` into a *set-valued* helper (partial rule) so all candidate IDs collect into one set, then `event_matches_secret(event)` succeeds when `secret_arn` is in that set. Roughly:

```rego
event_secret_ids(event) := ids if {
    ids := {x | x := object.get(event, "secret_arn", ""); x != ""} |
           {x | x := object.get(object.get(event, "request_parameters", {}), "secret_arn", ""); x != ""} |
           ...
           {x | resource := object.get(event, "resources", [])[_]; x := object.get(resource, "ARN", object.get(resource, "arn", "")); x != ""}
}

event_matches_secret(event) if event_secret_ids(event)[secret_arn]
```

Add a regression test with both `requestParameters.secretId` (a short `secretId`) and `resources[].ARN` (the full ARN matching `secret_arn`) populated on the same event.
