Comment (policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego:119):
**`principal_region` raises a runtime `eval_conflict_error` on `Principal.AWS` arrays that span multiple mapped accounts (medium).** Same Rego `:=` function-conflict shape as the `event_secret_id` thread on `secretsmanager_access_administration_events.rego`. The body iterates `arn := principal_values(principal_entry)[_]` and computes a region for each arn; for a `Principal: {"AWS": ["arn:aws:iam::111111111111:role/x", "arn:aws:iam::222222222222:role/y"]}` with `data.account_id_to_region` mapping the two accounts to *different* regions, this body succeeds twice with different region values, and OPA aborts:

```
eval_conflict_error: functions must not produce multiple outputs for same inputs
  policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego:117
```

This is a regression introduced by the same commit that added `Principal.AWS`-array support: the array form is the exact case the fix was intended to handle, but `principal_region` is a function (single-valued), so the array iteration breaks it at runtime.

Suggested fix: make `principal_region` set-valued, e.g.

```rego
principal_regions(principal_entry) := regions if {
    allow_effect(principal_entry)
    regions := {r |
        arn := principal_values(principal_entry)[_]
        acct := principal_account_id_from_value(arn)
        r := object.get(data.account_id_to_region, acct, "")
        r != ""
    }
}
```

then in the first `cross_border_principal_undocumented` rule iterate `region := principal_regions(principal)[_]` and check it against `allowed_pi_transfer_regions`. Add a regression test with a `{"AWS": [...]}` array of ARNs in two different mapped accounts.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_access_administration_events.rego, replace the six complete-function bodies event_secret_id(event) := id with a single set-valued helper such as event_secret_ids(event) := ids. Build ids as the union of all non-empty candidate IDs from event.secret_arn, event.request_parameters.secret_arn, event.request_parameters.secret_id, event.requestParameters.secretArn, event.requestParameters.secretId, and each event.resources[_].ARN/arn. Then change event_matches_secret(event) to check membership with event_secret_ids(event)[secret_arn] instead of event_secret_id(event) == secret_arn. Keep the helper local to this flat policy package; do not introduce a shared Rego package. Add a regression test where one CloudTrail admin event has both requestParameters.secretId set to a short name and resources[0].ARN set to the full secret_arn, and assert evaluation succeeds and the event matches without eval_conflict_error.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_confidential_disposal_record.rego, make the same local change as the access-administration policy: replace the six event_secret_id(event) := id complete-function bodies with a set-valued event_secret_ids(event) := ids helper that unions all non-empty candidate IDs from snake_case request_parameters, camelCase requestParameters, and resources[].ARN/arn. Update event_matches_secret(event) to use event_secret_ids(event)[secret_arn]. Do not share the helper across packages. Add a regression test with a DeleteSecret event containing both requestParameters.secretId and resources[0].ARN for the same secret, and assert delete_secret_events is evaluable and the disposal-record violations remain reachable.
Implementation guidance: In policies/secretsmanager_privacy_transfer_governance.rego, replace the single-valued principal_region(principal_entry) := region helper with a set-valued principal_regions(principal_entry) := regions helper. The helper should require allow_effect(principal_entry), iterate arn := principal_values(principal_entry)[_], derive principal_account := principal_account_id_from_value(arn), look up region := object.get(data.account_id_to_region, principal_account, ""), and include only non-empty regions in the returned set. Update the first violation[{"id": "cross_border_principal_undocumented"}] rule to use region := principal_regions(principal)[_] and check not allowed_pi_transfer_regions[region]. Keep the existing count(data.account_id_to_region) > 0 gate and the second account-id fallback rule unchanged except for any formatting needed. Add a regression test with Principal.AWS as an array of two ARNs mapped to different regions so evaluation succeeds and reports only regions outside data.allowed_pi_transfer_regions.
